The conditions need to, somehow, combine information from two different types of data:
- Design space geometry is the first: something has to happen when `weight > 0.5`. These values relate to how the masters are placed in the designspace.
- The other type of information is **when** a rule is expected to be applied and **which glyphs** are involved.

- It would be useful to be able to change `weight > 0.5` to `weight > 0.4` without having to edit the whole feature file. Maybe not all `weight > 0.5` statements are the same.
- The decision to need a specific conditional switch somewhere would not need to depend on knowing the exact axis values. 

Maybe there is a way to separate the **definition** of the condition (with its geometric references) and its **application** within the feature blocks. A set of named rules, each with any number of conditions is defined somewhere in the beginning of the feature text. Then whenever it is needed in the feature text, a rule can be invoked by name.

In fantasy feature text:
```
# before other code, define a rule with a set of conditions:
rule oslashcounter {
     wght 0.7 1;
     wdth 0.5 1;
} oslashcounter;

# then inside a feature block, call the name of the rule to have it evaluated
feature aaaa{
     sub @something by @somethingelse;
     if oslashcounter sub Oslash by Oslash.nocounter;
}aaaa;

# or perhaps even group some subs together in a single conditional block
feature bbbb{
     sub @something by @somethingelse;
     if oslashcounter {
          sub Oslash by Oslash.nocounter;
          sub oslash by oslash.nocounter;
     }
}bbbb;
``````
- easier to cluster substitutions
- single place to modify a designspace value
- allows the designer to experiment with rules and substitutions (and record results) even when the features are not ready.
- different tools can be used to edit and proof, and can be done by different people at different times.
- let's avoid having to use normalised coordinates in the feature text.

