Update: I got dynamic imports of npm modules working in a lab/notebook extension!

![screencast](http://g.recordit.co/n16ZJeon5u.gif)

To clarify, the extension is actually fetching the npm module in the browser, so now you can render data in a Jupyter notebook using **any React component on npm** with only the name and valid props. The really interesting things are:

* Rendering data is no longer dependent on the client or client extensions (meaning that users need not install an extension in order to render a specific type of data)
* React components can be rendered as static markup (nbviewer)
* Beyond the scope of this conversation, I see a big opportunity with inferring JSON schema from arbitrary data + querying React components that can render that schema = inferring visualization from arbitrary data.

The catches are:

* React version conflicts: https://github.com/systemjs/systemjs/issues/1511
* React components that rely on CSS styles (vs. inline styles)

It's using SystemJS to do the imports. The gist of the implementation is:

```js
import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom';

function render({ type, props }, node) {
  System.import(type).then(type => {
    ReactDOM.render(React.createElement(type, props, null), node);
  });
}
```

The usage inside the notebook looks like this:

```py
from IPython.display import display

def React(type, props):
    bundle = {
        'application/vnd.react.v1+json': {
            'type': type,
            'props': props
        },
        'application/json': props,
        'text/plain': '<IPython.core.display.React.object>'
    }
    display(bundle, raw=True)

React('react-json-tree', {
    'data': [
        {'month': 'September', 'profit': 35000, 'loss': 2000},
        {'month': 'October', 'profit': 42000, 'loss': 8000},
        {'month': 'November', 'profit': 55000, 'loss': 5000}
    ],
    'theme': 'google'
})
```

..or if you want to use a non-default member of an import:

```py
React({
    'module': 'victory',
    'member': 'VictoryBar'
}, {
    'data': [
        {'month': 'September', 'profit': 35000, 'loss': 2000},
        {'month': 'October', 'profit': 42000, 'loss': 8000},
        {'month': 'November', 'profit': 55000, 'loss': 5000}
    ],
    'x': 'month',
    'y': 'profit'
})
```

